comment:
My input is generally in support of the staff map that was released on 9/3/21 and strongly opposed to the Lafoya map that splits my home district of Boulder County into three separate Congressional Districts. It is absolutely critical to safeguard Boulder’s communities of interest that share critical environmental needs and climate goals (including how we respond to natural disasters such as the major fires, droughts and floods that have become our new normal), urgent transportation and infrastructure priorities, critical economic interdependencies, public health concerns (including most recently our collaborative response to the COVID 19 pandemic), and keeping our communities safe (which has become a key priority following the recent massacre of 10 Boulder residents at a local King Soopers market). The greater Boulder community is made up of a complex and collaborative set of diverse communities of interest (city, suburban, mountain, rural) that must be able to continue to work together with representation by a shared Member of Congress. 

Zooming out from Boulder County to consider the overall needs of our state in this important redistricting process, I can offer the following observations on the most recent staff map:
* making CD2 a more NW district will help give rural Coloradans better representation and combine mountain communities in order to extend urgent environmental attention westward;
* it is important to keep all of Summit County’s Gateway to the Rockies communities of interest together in CD7; 
* the proposed changes to CD3, which honor the historical ties between the Pueblo & the San Luis Valley, is a positive step in reuniting these important communities of interest and making it a more competitive district;
* it is critical that the new CD8 reflect the reality of CO’s population shifts over the past decade, so I generally support it as proposed to include important minority communities along the I-25 corridor.

Thank you for taking the time to consider my input and for your important work serving all Coloradans on this redistricting commission.

Respectfully submitted,

Bernardita Z. Hutchinson
Boulder, CO

The first staff plan map largely ignores agriculture and rural Colorado's unique community of interest by combining it with urban and suburban populations;
fails to reflect the differences in water administration, ag industry makeup, and social landscape between eastern and western parts of the state;
ignores testimony from around the state regarding desired district lines.

The "First Staff Plan" map
Is a non-starter for rural Colorado;
Ignores agriculture and rural Colorado's unique community of interest by combining it with urban and suburban populations;
Fails to reflect the differences in water administration, ag industry makeup, and social landscape between eastern and western parts of the state;
Ignores testimony from around the state regarding desired district lines.
 Commissioners please recognize rural Colorado as a distinct community of interest with the same public policy concerns based on agriculture, employment, and water needs and supplies, which are different from urban and suburban communities, and captured in the "Preliminary plan.
